				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Typ=
e of statistical measure over subsets of a dataset</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving-average_model" titl=
e=3D"Moving-average model">Moving-average model</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig=
" title=3D"Moving average (disambiguation)">Moving average (disambiguation)=
</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lissage_sinus_bruite_moyenne_glissante.svg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikip=
edia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Lissage_sinus_bruite_moyenne_glissante.svg/250px-Li=
ssage_sinus_bruite_moyenne_glissante.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
50" height=3D"186" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"487" data-f=
ile-height=3D"362"></a><figcaption>Smoothing of a noisy sine (blue curve) w=
ith a moving average (red curve).</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, a <b>moving average</b> (<b>rolling average</b> or <b>=
running average</b> or <b>moving mean</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite_note-=
1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> or <b>rolling mean</b>) is a calculation to analyze data poin=
ts by creating a series of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average=
" title=3D"Average">averages</a> of different selections of the full data s=
et. Variations include: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_ave=
rage#Simple_moving_average">simple</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Moving_average#Cumulative_average">cumulative</a>, or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#Weighted_moving_average">weighted<=
/a> forms.
</p><p>Mathematically, a moving average is a type of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution" title=3D"Convolution">convolution</a>. Thus=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D"Si=
gnal processing">signal processing</a> it is viewed as a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-pass_filter" title=3D"Low-pass filter">low-pass<=
/a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_impulse_response" title=
=3D"Finite impulse response">finite impulse response</a> filter. Because th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boxcar_function" title=3D"Boxcar=
 function">boxcar function</a> outlines its filter coefficients, it is call=
ed a <b>boxcar filter</b>. It is sometimes followed by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Downsampling_(signal_processing)" title=3D"Downsamplin=
g (signal processing)">downsampling</a>.
</p><p>Given a series of numbers and a fixed subset size, the first element=
 of the moving average is obtained by taking the average of the initial fix=
ed subset of the number series. Then the subset is modified by "shifting fo=
rward"; that is, excluding the first number of the series and including the=
 next value in the series.
</p><p>A moving average is commonly used with <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Time_series" title=3D"Time series">time series</a> data to smoo=
th out short-term fluctuations and highlight longer-term trends or cycles -=
 in this case the calculation is sometimes called a <b>time average</b>. Th=
e threshold between short-term and long-term depends on the application, an=
d the parameters of the moving average will be set accordingly. It is also =
used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Econom=
ics">economics</a> to examine gross domestic product, employment or other m=
acroeconomic time series. When used with non-time series data, a moving ave=
rage filters higher frequency components without any specific connection to=
 time, although typically some kind of ordering is implied. Viewed simplist=
ically it can be regarded as smoothing the data.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
