<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Weighted_moving_average">We=
ighted moving average</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DMoving_average&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Weighted moving average"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A weighted average is an average that has multiplying factors to give di=
fferent weights to data at different positions in the sample window. Mathem=
atically, the weighted moving average is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Convolution" title=3D"Convolution">convolution</a> of the data w=
ith a fixed weighting function. One application is removing <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixelization" title=3D"Pixelization">pixelization=
</a> from a digital graphical image. This is also known as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-aliasing" title=3D"Anti-aliasing">Anti-aliasi=
ng</a> <sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-=
space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citat=
ion_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim n=
eeds references to reliable sources. (February 2018)">citation needed</span=
></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In the financial field, and more specifically in the analyses of fin=
ancial data, a <b>weighted moving average</b> (WMA) has the specific meanin=
g of weights that decrease in arithmetical progression.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_aver=
age#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> In an <i>n</i>-day WMA the latest day has weigh=
t <i>n</i>, the second latest <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-elem=
ent-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" sty=
le=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" al=
ttext=3D"{\displaystyle n-1}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
