<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Exponential_moving_average"=
><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Exponential"></span>Exponential moving averag=
e</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMoving_ave=
rage&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Exponential =
moving average"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_smoothin=
g" title=3D"Exponential smoothing">Exponential smoothing</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EWMA_chart" t=
itle=3D"EWMA chart">EWMA chart</a></div>
<p>An <b>exponential moving average (EMA)</b>, also known as an <b>exponent=
ially weighted moving average (EWMA)</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite_note-=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> is a first-order <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inf=
inite_impulse_response" title=3D"Infinite impulse response">infinite impuls=
e response</a> filter that applies weighting factors which decrease <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_decay" title=3D"Exponential d=
ecay">exponentially</a>. The weighting for each older <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">datum</a> decreases exponentially,=
 never reaching zero.=20
This formulation is according to Hunter (1986).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite=
_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There is also a multivariate implementation of EWMA, known as MEWMA.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Moving_average#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_weightings">Other wei=
ghtings</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMovi=
ng_average&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Other =
weightings"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Other weighting systems are used occasionally =E2=80=93 for example, in =
share trading a <b>volume weighting</b> will weight each time period in pro=
portion to its trading volume.
</p><p>A further weighting, used by actuaries, is Spencer's 15-Point Moving=
 Average<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (a central moving a=
verage). Its symmetric weight coefficients are [=E2=88=923, =E2=88=926, =E2=
=88=925, 3, 21, 46, 67, 74, 67, 46, 21, 3, =E2=88=925, =E2=88=926, =E2=88=
=923], which factors as <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"=
><span class=3D"num">[1, 1, 1, 1]=C3=97[1, 1, 1, 1]=C3=97[1, 1, 1, 1, 1]=C3=
=97[=E2=88=923, 3, 4, 3, =E2=88=923]</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span>=
<span class=3D"den">320</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> and leaves samples of=
 any quadratic or cubic polynomial unchanged.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite=
_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Outside the world of finance, weighted running means have many forms=
 and applications. Each weighting function or "kernel" has its own characte=
ristics. In engineering and science the frequency and phase response of the=
 filter is often of primary importance in understanding the desired and und=
esired distortions that a particular filter will apply to the data.
</p><p>A mean does not just "smooth" the data. A mean is a form of low-pass=
 filter. The effects of the particular filter used should be understood in =
order to make an appropriate choice.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template T=
emplate-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed=
"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2=
025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Moving_median">Moving media=
n</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMoving_ave=
rage&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Moving media=
n"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>From a statistical point of view, the moving average, when used to estim=
ate the underlying trend in a time series, is susceptible to rare events su=
ch as rapid shocks or other anomalies. A more robust estimate of the trend =
is the <b>simple moving median</b> over <i>n</i> time points:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\widetilde {p}}_{\text{SM}}=3D{\text{Median}}(p_{M},p_{M-1},\l=
dots ,p_{M-n+1})}">
  <semantics>
